hat we might occasionally allocate a page and then free it again?<br /><br />Why are gfs2 and cifs doing things wrong?<br /><br />"readpage()" is not for synchrionizing metadata. Never has been. You<br />shouldn't treat it that way, and you shouldn't then make excuses for<br />filesystems that treat it that way.<br /><br />Look at mmap, for example. It will do the SIGBUS handling before<br />calling readpage(). Same goes for the copyfile code. A filesystem that<br />thinks "I will update size at readpage" is already fundamentally<br />buggy.<br /><br />We do _recheck_ the inode size under the page lock, but that's to<br />handle the races with truncate etc.<br /><br />            Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
